Globnobulous - Teacher & Founder

# [25-01-2026] - Second Semester

First semester was good but intense.  I last taught this course with **chalk**.
iPads and laptops in the lecturing context was new to me.  Also, 12 hours a
week on campus was a big, but welcome departure from 8 years working from
home.

The engineering students are still overworked but trying hard for the most 
part.  Learning, getting things done.  Their energy is inspiring :)

Also, turns out I enjoy setting programming exams.  I guess it's really just
puzzle making, and puzzles are a big component of games.  So I'm making puzzles
for a game that gives you magic undergraduate degree credits as your 
reward for solving them well enough and fast enough.

Of course I like it :D

## Rolling into a new semester
Now I'm only teaching 1 section of a first year programming course where the material 
is on the level of

```
    A for loop is structured like so:

    for (<initialize>; <condition>; <increment>) {
        <body>;
    }
```

This does not require the same level of practice or prep that, say, Complexity Analysis 
of Iterative & Recursive Algorithms does.  So DepSys projects are waking up and 
making progress, which is exciting!

For example, the framework for this website has been greatly expanded on, not 
leastwise because of the efforts of my **Bright Young Apprentice**.  If you know anything
about unix or command lines, I urge you to press q right now and see what this
little framework can do :)

## Concursion
Most importantly, I've made a lot of progress on the concursion engine!  The current challenge
is to select a unit and send it somewhere.  I've started at the highest level of mobility,
with ships following Keplerian trajectories in gravity wells, and to test I've got a scale
accurate model of our solarsystem.

![Orrery](orrery.gif) 

My test sets up a ship in LEO, and I need to plot a trajectory to the moon

![TransferOrbit](transferorbit.gif)

If you're patient watching the above, you'll see where the orbital calculations go off the rails :D

It becomes super obvious when we print out the starting position vector of our calculated transfer 
trajectory once per frame.  You don't even have to read the values to know something has gone horribly
wrong!
![HyperbolicParaboloid](hyperbolicparaboloid.png)

There's something specific about this range of initial conditions that blows up my implementation
of Hyperbolic Orbits, and neither Claude nor GPT can seem to figure it out.  So I *get to* (not *have
to*!) dig in and learn something new about the maths of Keplerian orbits. :D

Will try for a fast follow with my findings!